<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 12:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I29fbc4d0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>12.</label.designator><headtext>Burdens and Presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id72176a4682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>12:5.</label.designator><headtext>Affirmative defenses in criminal cases—Specific defenses</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>When a criminal defendant raises an affirmative defense, he essentially admits the act charged, but seeks to justify, excuse, or mitigate it.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9b8907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] With an affirmative defense, the focus is no longer the act itself, but the introduction of evidence that disputes the defendant&apos;s alleged justification or excuse for the act.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9b8917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] However, practitioners must be aware that when raising self-defense or defense of habitation, the accused must admit all the elements of the crime except intent.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9b8927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Georgia recognizes many affirmative defenses.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9b8937fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GASTT16C3" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1a30c07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. Title 16, Ch. 3</cite.query>, Art. 2 lists six affirmative defenses[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9b8947fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] to criminal liability: justification,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9b8957fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] defense of self or others,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] defense of habitation,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] defense of property,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] entrapment,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] and coercion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>“When the statutory affirmative defenses were set out, it was <page no="423"/>probably thought that the burden of proof as to these defenses would be placed on the defendant.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>] In the case of some specific defenses, such as “entrapment” and “accident,” the Georgia courts have placed the burden on the defendant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6b9dfa67fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13</footnote.reference>] Even so, the Council of Superior Court Judges has chosen to eliminate instructions placing the burden of proof on the defendant to establish any affirmative defense in its Criminal Charge Book.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba06b07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">14</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Some well-known criminal defenses, such as “alibi,”[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba06b17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">15</footnote.reference>] are not “affirmative defenses” and do not actually shift the burden of persuasion to the defendant.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Accident is a recognized affirmative defense in Georgia[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba06b27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">16</footnote.reference>] for which the state has the burden of disproving the defense beyond a reasonable doubt.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba06b37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">17</footnote.reference>] However, the defendant bears the burden of establishing that he <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“acted without criminal intent and was not engaged in a criminal scheme, and that [his] actions did not show “‘an utter disregard for the safety of others who might reasonably be expected to be injured thereby.’<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>”[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba06b47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">18</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Self-defense is probably the most well-known of all criminal defenses. <eos/><bos/>It is codified as an affirmative defense in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e23f4c07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 16-<page no="424"/>3-21</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-28" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e23f4c17fc011ea988285db8533e975">16-3-28</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>However, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975132027" w-seq-number="00039" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e23f4c47fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Henderson v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba2dc07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">19</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court held that self-defense was not an affirmative defense and that a jury charge placing the burden as to self-defense on the defendant was error in light of the United States Supreme Court&apos;s ruling in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975129799" w-seq-number="00041" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I6e24b8127fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Mullaney v. Wilbur.</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba2dc17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">20</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Three years later, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1978132390" w-seq-number="00043" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e257b627fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Holloway v. McElroy</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba2dc27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">21</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court changed course and held that self-defense was an affirmative defense. <eos/><bos/>This change was short-lived,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba2dc37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">22</footnote.reference>] and the Georgia Supreme Court has since clarified that the state bears the burden of proving beyond a reasonable doubt that the defendant did not act in self-defense regardless of how the defense is categorized.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba2dc47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">23</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>“Battered person syndrome” has become a popular self-defense for which evidence supporting the syndrome is admissible only to assist the jury in evaluating a defendant&apos;s claim of self-defense.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba2dc57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">24</footnote.reference>] A defendant may use battered person or other similar syndromes to show that he lacked the requisite intent to commit the crime charged.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba54d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">25</footnote.reference>] The state bears the burden of establishing defendant&apos;s intent to commit the offense charged and the defendant, claiming to have suffered from a particular syndrome, will not bear the burden of proving the effects thereof.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>It is an affirmative defense that a defendant abandoned his effort to commit the crime, or in any other manner prevented its commission under circumstances manifesting a voluntary and <page no="425"/>complete renunciation of the criminal purpose. <eos/><bos/>The state has the burden of disproving the defense beyond a reasonable doubt.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ba54d17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">26</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic6b9b8907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2037237036" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e185c027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Klemetti v. State, 334 Ga. App. 513, 780 S.E.2d 346 (2015)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2039763784" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e185c057fc011ea988285db8533e975">State v. Alvarez, 299 Ga. 213, 790 S.E.2d 66 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9b8917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2001326468" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e18d1327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bacon v. State, 249 Ga. App. 347, 349, 548 S.E.2d 78 (2001)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9b8927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2044786376" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e191f527fc011ea988285db8533e975">McClure v. State, 347 Ga. App. 68, 815 S.E.2d 313 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9b8937fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See e.g., <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-3-1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1994807fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 17-3-1</cite.query> (limitation); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-1-8" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1994817fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-1-8</cite.query> (double jeopardy); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1994827fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-1 (age)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-5" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1994837fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-5</cite.query> (mistake of fact); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-4-5" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1994847fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-4-5</cite.query> (abandonment).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9b8947fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-28" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1a57d07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-28</cite.query> provides: <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“A defense based upon any of the provisions of this article is an affirmative defense.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9b8957fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-20" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1aa5f07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-20</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1b1b207fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-21</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2035533989" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1b1b237fc011ea988285db8533e975">Parrott v. State, 330 Ga. App. 801, 769 S.E.2d 549 (2015)</cite.query>, the Court of Appeals held it was not error for the trial court to charge the jury with an instruction on defendant&apos;s self-defense where the defendant did not ask for such instruction at trial.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-23" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1b69407fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-23</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-24" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1bb7607fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-24</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-25" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1bde707fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-25</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="423"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1974127876" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1d65127fc011ea988285db8533e975">Reed v. State, 130 Ga. App. 659, 204 S.E.2d 335 (1974)</cite.query> (disapproved of <case.history>on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1976115787" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1d65157fc011ea988285db8533e975">Cook v. State, 137 Ga. App. 406, 224 S.E.2d 70 (1976)</cite.query>), held that, in spite of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-25" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1d65167fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 16-3-25</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-28" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1d65177fc011ea988285db8533e975">16-3-28</cite.query>, entrapment could not be made an affirmative defense because it would violate due process. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1974127876" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1d651a7fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Reed</ital></cite.query> was followed in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975130429" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1d651d7fc011ea988285db8533e975">McNeill v. State, 134 Ga. App. 45, 213 S.E.2d 119 (1975)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>However, the Georgia Supreme Court subsequently reversed the Court of Appeals in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975130429" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1d65207fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>McNeill</ital></cite.query> and held that entrapment was a valid affirmative defense. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975131615" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1d65237fc011ea988285db8533e975">State v. McNeill, 234 Ga. 696, 217 S.E.2d 281 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-3-26" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e1e01507fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-3-26</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Goger, Daniel&apos;s Ga. Criminal Trial Practice (2018–2019 ed.) § 21:17.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6b9dfa67fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See Goger, Daniel&apos;s Ga. Criminal Trial Practice (2018–2019 ed.) § 21:17; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975131615" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1faf027fc011ea988285db8533e975">State v. McNeill, 234 Ga. 696, 217 S.E.2d 281 (1975)</cite.query> (entrapment); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1973127720" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e1faf057fc011ea988285db8533e975">Chandle v. State, 230 Ga. 574, 576, 198 S.E.2d 289 (1973)</cite.query> (accident).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The courts have held that in order to receive jury instructions for entrapment, a defendant must first admit that he committed the crime; otherwise, it would be factually inconsistent to complain that the defendant was entrapped. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2038252208" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2024327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Murray v. State, 335 Ga. App. 634, 782 S.E.2d 694 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba06b07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Goger, Daniel&apos;s Ga. Criminal Trial Practice (2018–2019 ed.) § 21:17.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba06b17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975130565" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2183c27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Patterson v. State, 233 Ga. 724, 213 S.E.2d 612 (1975)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2000079746" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2183c57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Cowan v. State, 243 Ga. App. 388, 531 S.E.2d 785 (2000)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba06b27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>16</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-2-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I6e2220007fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-2-2</cite.query> provides: <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“A person shall not be found guilty of any crime committed by misfortune or accident where it satisfactorily appears there was no criminal scheme or undertaking, intention, or criminal negligence.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1973127720" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e226e227fc011ea988285db8533e975">Chandle v. State, 230 Ga. 574, 198 S.E.2d 289 (1973)</cite.query>, holding “accident” to be a true affirmative defense.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba06b37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>17</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2016215110" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e22bc427fc011ea988285db8533e975">Walton v. State, 291 Ga. App. 736, 662 S.E.2d 820 (2008)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba06b47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>18</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1998061928" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2331727fc011ea988285db8533e975">Davis v. State, 269 Ga. 276, 279, 496 S.E.2d 699 (1998)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2016121224" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2331757fc011ea988285db8533e975">Dunagan v. State, 283 Ga. 501, 661 S.E.2d 525 (2008)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="424"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba2dc07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>19</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975132027" w-seq-number="00040" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2442e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Henderson v. State, 234 Ga. 827, 218 S.E.2d 612 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba2dc17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>20</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1975129799" w-seq-number="00042" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I6e2506327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Mullaney v. Wilbur, 421 U.S. 684, 95 S. Ct. 1881, 44 L. Ed. 2d 508 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba2dc27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>21</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1978132390" w-seq-number="00044" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e25a2727fc011ea988285db8533e975">Holloway v. McElroy, 241 Ga. 400, 245 S.E.2d 658 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba2dc37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>22</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1979116909" w-seq-number="00045" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I6e2617a17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Holloway v. McElroy, 474 F. Supp. 1363 (M.D. Ga. 1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1981225653" w-seq-number="00046" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I6e2617a47fc011ea988285db8533e975">McElroy v. Holloway, 451 U.S. 1028, 101 S. Ct. 3019, 69 L. Ed. 2d 398 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba2dc47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>23</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1984145562" w-seq-number="00047" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e26b3e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">State v. Shepperd, 253 Ga. 321, 320 S.E.2d 154 (1984)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1991202822" w-seq-number="00048" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e26b3e57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hollis v. State, 201 Ga. App. 224, 411 S.E.2d 48 (1991)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2002569037" w-seq-number="00049" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e26b3e87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Heard v. State, 257 Ga. App. 315, 573 S.E.2d 82 (2002)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2042324195" w-seq-number="00050" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e26b3eb7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Woodward v. State, 342 Ga. App. 499, 804 S.E.2d 153 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>But see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1987024299" w-seq-number="00051" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I6e2777327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Martin v. Ohio, 480 U.S. 228, 107 S. Ct. 1098, 94 L. Ed. 2d 267 (1987)</cite.query>, wherein the court held that the Fourteenth Amendment Due Process Clause does not prevent a state from placing the burden of proving self-defense on a defendant when he was tried for murder. <eos/><bos/>The court noted, however, that Ohio and South Carolina were the only states that still made self-defense an affirmative defense. <eos/><bos/>The charge that the defendant had the burden to establish self-defense by a preponderance of the evidence was proper, but only where the jury was also charged that even though the defendant had not carried his burden, his evidence could be used by the jury to find a reasonable doubt as to his guilt.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba2dc57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>24</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="1999177242" w-seq-number="00052" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e27ec627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Graham v. State, 239 Ga. App. 429, 521 S.E.2d 249 (1999)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba54d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>25</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2009561904" w-seq-number="00053" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e2861927fc011ea988285db8533e975">Pickle v. State, 280 Ga. App. 821, 635 S.E.2d 197 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="425"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ba54d17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>26</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017237" w-serial-number="2047693132" w-seq-number="00054" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I6e28fdd27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Reid v. State, 349 Ga. App. 196, 825 S.E.2d 555 (2019)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 12:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
